When Wolf was rushed to the emergency vet, his family was told he had a 0–10% chance of survival. The estimate for emergency exploratory surgery was $13,000 — due upfront.

This is the story of how one dog's fight for survival revealed a crisis that affects millions of families and their pets every year: the access to care gap.

## The Moment Everything Changed

Wolf wasn't a rescue. He wasn't neglected. He was a beloved family member who got sick. And when the emergency came, his family faced the same impossible decision that thousands of families face every day — not whether to try, but whether they could afford to.

## What Wolf Taught Us

Wolf survived. But his survival wasn't guaranteed by medicine alone — it was made possible by access. Someone opened a door. Someone made sure cost wasn't the final answer.

That's why The Wolf Project exists. Because no family should lose their dog simply because they can't afford the chance to say yes.

## What Comes Next

The Wolf Project is building an Access to Care Lifeline — a fund that steps in when emergency veterinary costs stand between a dog and the life-saving treatment they need. We're in Phase 1 right now, building the foundation responsibly so that when we say yes to the first case, we can fully stand behind it.

Stay connected. Join the pack. And help us make sure the next dog gets the same chance Wolf did.
